<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Methodology</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    The estimator is an educational tool, not a valuation model. It exists to give a reader a defensible answer to the question
    &ldquo;what order of magnitude is this kind of case worth?&rdquo; so the reader walks into a free consultation with a lawyer
    already knowing which questions matter. The math is deliberately transparent; the inputs deliberately broad.
  </p>

  <h2>Damages components recognized under Title VII</h2>
  <p>
    A successful Title VII sexual harassment plaintiff can recover four discrete categories of relief. The Civil Rights Act of 1991
    added compensatory and punitive damages on top of the equitable remedies (back pay, front pay, reinstatement, injunctive relief)
    that were available under the 1964 statute.
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Back pay.</strong> Wages, bonuses, commissions, and the dollar value of lost benefits from the adverse action through
      the date of judgment or settlement, offset by interim earnings (the duty to mitigate). Back pay is equitable relief outside the
      damages cap and is generally treated as wages for tax purposes.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Front pay.</strong> Future earnings the plaintiff would have received but for the unlawful conduct, where reinstatement
      is impractical. Equitable, not always awarded, and not within the cap (<em>Pollard v. E.I. du Pont de Nemours &amp; Co.</em>, 532 U.S. 843 (2001)).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Compensatory damages.</strong> Out-of-pocket losses plus non-economic harm: emotional distress, mental anguish, loss of
      enjoyment of life, medical and therapy costs, harm to professional reputation.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Punitive damages.</strong> Available only against private employers (not governments) and only on proof of malice or
      reckless indifference to federally protected rights (<em>Kolstad v. American Dental Ass&rsquo;n</em>, 527 U.S. 526 (1999)).
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The 42 U.S.C. &sect; 1981a(b)(3) employer-size cap</h2>
  <p>
    Combined compensatory plus punitive damages under Title VII are capped by the employer&rsquo;s number of US employees in each of
    20 or more calendar weeks of the current or preceding calendar year:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>15&ndash;100 employees:</strong> $50,000 combined cap.</li>
    <li><strong>101&ndash;200 employees:</strong> $100,000 combined cap.</li>
    <li><strong>201&ndash;500 employees:</strong> $200,000 combined cap.</li>
    <li><strong>501+ employees:</strong> $300,000 combined cap.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    These caps have not been raised for inflation since 1991. They are per-plaintiff, per-statute, not per-claim. Back pay, front pay,
    and attorney fees fall outside the cap, which is why fee-shifting under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-5(k) often exceeds the damages award
    in modest-employer cases.
  </p>

  <h2>State alternatives that uncap or expand recovery</h2>
  <p>
    The federal cap drives plaintiffs into parallel state claims wherever the state statute is more generous. The estimator widens
    the upper range when the state field maps to one of the following.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>California FEHA (Gov. Code &sect; 12940 et seq.):</strong> no damages cap; 3-year filing window (AB 9, 2020); fee-shifting; covers employers with 5+ employees for harassment.</li>
    <li><strong>New York Human Rights Law (Exec. Law &sect; 296):</strong> no damages cap as amended in 2019; covers all employers regardless of size for harassment; 3-year statute of limitations on sexual harassment (CPLR 214-g amendments).</li>
    <li><strong>New Jersey LAD:</strong> no cap; broad emotional-distress recovery; punitive damages available.</li>
    <li><strong>Illinois Human Rights Act:</strong> no cap as amended; covers employers with 1+ employee for harassment.</li>
    <li><strong>Massachusetts G.L. c. 151B:</strong> no cap; treble back-pay availability in certain circumstances.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Worked example: hostile environment, mid-size employer, no termination</h2>
  <p>
    A 32-year-old marketing manager at a 300-employee private company in Texas reports two years of unwelcome sexual comments
    and three propositions from her department head. She still works there. Annual income $80,000, three-year tenure.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Severity: severe (repeated, supervisor) &rarr; compensatory midpoint ~$175,000.</li>
    <li>Claim type: hostile environment &rarr; multiplier 1.0.</li>
    <li>No adverse employment action &rarr; back pay near $0.</li>
    <li>Employer size 201&ndash;500 &rarr; $200,000 federal cap on combined comp + punitive.</li>
    <li>Texas overlay: no FEHA-style uncapping. The federal cap controls.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Educational range output roughly $96,000&ndash;$290,000, with the high end approaching the statutory cap if punitive damages are
    realistic. Real-world settlements in this profile cluster $75,000&ndash;$250,000, with the trial-risk premium nudging either direction
    based on documentary evidence and the strength of the <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em> defense.
  </p>

  <h2>Worked example: quid pro quo with constructive discharge, large employer, California</h2>
  <p>
    A 28-year-old senior associate at a 2,000-employee firm in San Francisco refuses her partner&rsquo;s repeated propositions; her hours
    are stripped, her reviews tank, she resigns four months later. Annual income $140,000, four-year tenure.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Severity: egregious (supervisor abuse of power) &rarr; compensatory midpoint ~$400,000.</li>
    <li>Claim type: quid pro quo &rarr; multiplier 1.15.</li>
    <li>Constructive discharge &rarr; back pay roughly one year salary plus mitigation discount &asymp; $105,000, plus modest front pay.</li>
    <li>California: FEHA uncapped &mdash; no federal cap ceiling.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Educational range output roughly $310,000&ndash;$900,000. Real settlements in this profile, with documentary evidence, frequently
    land $400,000&ndash;$1,200,000, plus fee-shifted attorney fees that can match or exceed the damages award.
  </p>

  <h2>What the estimator deliberately ignores</h2>
  <p>
    Jurisdiction-specific jury attitudes, the identity of opposing counsel, the employer&rsquo;s insurance posture, prior similar
    settlements within the same company, the plaintiff&rsquo;s credibility on the stand, and the trial-risk premium each side prices
    in privately. Those are the variables that actually move a case in mediation; none of them are knowable from a web form.
  </p>

